    "content": "<p>In the BJT circuit shown, beta of the PNP transistor is 100 . Assume $V_{B E}=-0.7 \\mathrm{~V}$. The voltage across $R_C$ will be 5 V when $R_2$ is $\\_\\_\\_\\_$ $\\mathrm{k} \\Omega$. (Round off to 2 decimal places)</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh61wg2e/c8a88224-9c78-4959-a032-d1438e81984a/385e7f60-b181-11f0-9ec5-a735814724b3/file-jaoe38c1mh61wg2f.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh61wg2e/c8a88224-9c78-4959-a032-d1438e81984a/385e7f60-b181-11f0-9ec5-a735814724b3/file-jaoe38c1mh61wg2f.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"GATE EE 2021 Analog Electronics - Bjt and Mosfet Biasing Question 1 English\"></p>",
    "options": [],
    "correct_options": [],
    "answer": "18.099",
    "explanation": "<p>Given :</p>\n<p>(i) $\\beta=100$</p>\n<p>(ii) $V_{B E}=-0.7 \\mathrm{~V}$</p>\n<p>(iii) $V_s=12 \\mathrm{~V}$</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/jaoe38c1mh61werg/479beb05-ad4b-4f0c-b0f2-0b31a6d71453/375c9fc0-b181-11f0-9ec5-a735814724b3/file-jaoe38c1mh61werh.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/jaoe38c1mh61werg/479beb05-ad4b-4f0c-b0f2-0b31a6d71453/375c9fc0-b181-11f0-9ec5-a735814724b3/file-jaoe38c1mh61werh.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0 auto;max-height:40vh;vertical-align:baseline\" alt=\"GATE EE 2021 Analog Electronics - Bjt and Mosfet Biasing Question 1 English Explanation\">$$ \\begin{aligned} &amp; I_C=\\beta I_B \\\\ &amp; 1.51=100 I_B \\\\ &amp; I_B=1.51 \\times 10^{-2} \\mathrm{~mA} \\\\ &amp; I_E=(1+\\beta) I_B \\\\ &amp; I_E=1.52 \\mathrm{~mA} \\\\ &amp; 12-1.2 \\times 1.5251-0.7-V_{R_2}=0 \\\\ &amp; V_{R_2}=9.46988 \\\\ &amp; I=\\frac{12-9.46988}{4.7}=0.53 \\mathrm{~mA} \\\\ &amp; I_{R_2}=0.53-\\frac{1.51}{100}=0.52322 \\mathrm{~mA} \\\\ &amp; R_2=\\frac{V_{R_2}}{I_{R_2}}=\\frac{9.46988}{0.52322}=18.099 \\mathrm{k} \\Omega \\end{aligned} $$</p>",
